english:
  title: Record of the Training Hall Archery Range
  author: Sung Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Why is this hall called by the name of archery? Because it was established to cultivate martial prowess. The tools for cultivating martial prowess are not limited to archery alone, yet why is it named solely after archery? Because archery stands foremost among the five weapons—its naming carries profound significance.

    In times of peace, martial training serves to protect the people and maintain great stability, standing ready for use when necessity arises. When called upon, it can eliminate violence and rebellion, striking awe throughout heaven and earth. This is the power of prior cultivation. Thus the Training Hall Archery Range was established for this purpose.

    Our sovereign, continuing the legacy of ancestors and expanding their great achievements, has elevated the culture of letters to adorn his era with brilliance. Yet he forgets not that peace contains hidden danger and keeps his heart fixed upon military affairs, recognizing that this hall was established by his forebears. He has thus commanded me to record its origins and pass them to posterity.

    I reflect upon this truth: it is easier to govern when the realm is in chaos than to govern when it is at peace. When heaven and earth are in turmoil and heroes contend for power, the ruler's mind is ever vigilant, as though enemy nations lurked at his doorstep. But once the realm is settled and the land at rest, most men grow complacent in prosperity, falling into sloth and ease. They speak not of war, allowing vagrants and idlers from the marketplace to become the state's claws and fangs. Some even melt down their weapons to demonstrate disuse. Then one morning, crisis erupts. When common men rise up from the wilderness, the realm crumbles and dissolves. After fifty years of desperate struggle, such ruin follows. This is the natural course of things.

    Therefore it is said: "Though the realm be at peace, to forget warfare is to invite calamity." The ancient kings understood this. Though they exalted benevolence, righteousness, rites, and music to transform the world, they did not dare neglect the bow and arrow as instruments of defense. Thus the Office of the Grand Commander of Armies was established, and the Great Archery Ceremony and village archery contests were instituted. When the Zhou declined and the six arts fell into ruin, what remained after the fires of Qin was merely gathered fragments. The great principles were forgotten by the world, and day by day they wasted away—all because the expedient and shallow won out. Should this not be lamented?

    Our founder, bearing bow and quiver in hand, established the nation from nothing. With his great work accomplished and heaven's mandate bestowed, he recognized that though weapons might lie unused, military readiness must not be abandoned. He thus first brought forth the matter of training and cultivation. The great king Taejong, honoring his predecessor's achievements and pursuing his aims, established a hall to the east of the capital, opening wide its southern chamber—this is the archery range we speak of. He commanded the Ministry of War to gather soldiers under the supervision of local commanders and officials, holding great archery contests here.

    Their methods are fourfold: martial selection, general examination, talent recruitment, and talent cultivation—all designed to assess ability and encourage excellence, to observe diligence and administer reward and punishment, to distinguish courage from timidity and inspire virtue. Tigers and leopards are fashioned as targets, sleeves and finger guards donned, as soldiers strive and excel in vigor and joy. The use of spear, banner, drum, and bell is displayed in full—showing that the tools of military training extend far beyond archery alone. The work of governance and the deep foresight of preparation are most comprehensive.

    Now the prince continues this method without loss, maintaining utmost care. From within his broad halls upon fine cushions, he ever remembers his forebears' toil through wind and rain, seeking to preserve the heritage and bring peace to the people. In military matters, he trains daily and instructs monthly, practicing seasonally and discussing regularly. Thus the wise exhaust no technique, the brave expend no strength. The soldiers are refined, the troops strong—they can soar above heaven and earth and traverse mountain and sea.

    When we compare this to the emperors of Han and Tang, who made archery contests mere entertainment and sport, the difference in their models is immeasurable. Therefore this hall must be recorded. Thus I humbly set down this account.
  footnotes:
    - The 'five weapons' (五兵) refer to spear, halberd, sword, axe, and bow—with archery serving as the primary discipline
    - 'The ''six arts'' (六藝) of classical Zhou learning were: ritual, music, archery, charioteering, calligraphy, and mathematics'
    - Taejong (태종) refers to the second ruler of Joseon Dynasty, who established the Training Hall (Hunyeongwon) in Seoul
    - '''Soaring above heaven and earth'' is a poetic expression meaning to achieve perfect martial skill and harmony'
